03874nam a22005655i 9780774833318DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20162016xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748333187 a10.59962/97807748333182doi  a(DE-B1597)662162  a(OCoLC)955600973  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ1090 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a305.312231 aGarlick, Steve, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Nature of Masculinity :bCritical Theory, New Materialisms, and Technologies of Embodiment /cSteve Garlick. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (236 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSexuality Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tSocial Theory, Masculinity, and New Materialisms -- tTechnologies of Embodiment: Toward a New Critical Theory of Masculinity -- tAutoerotic Bodies: Biopolitics, Masculinity, and Nature -- tPornographic Bodies: Affect, Masculinity, and Technology -- tViolent Bodies: Complexity and the Spectacle of Masculinity -- tThe Work of Masculinity -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSocial theorists have argued that as the complexity of our ecosystems becomes more apparent, the line between nature and culture, human and nonhuman, and technology and bodies becomes less distinct. Yet contemporary masculinity studies has generally failed to incorporate this new way of thinking. In this penetrating analysis of the relationship between gender and nature, Steve Garlick proposes that masculinity is best understood as a technology that shapes both our engagement with the natural world and how we define freedom. Extending the work of the Frankfurt School and Heidegger’s critique of modern technology, The Nature of Masculinity draws on case studies and new materialist theories to argue that the essence of technology is not in mechanical devices but in a particular relationship to natural forces. Within this critical framework, masculinity is a technology of embodiment, and freedom does not lie in the domination of nature but rather in fostering a new relation to it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMasculinityxPhilosophy. 0aMasculinity--Philosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311127380808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016z978311127630408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311141795040uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483331840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774833318423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774833318/original  a978-3-11-127380-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-127630-4  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-141795-0  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles